:::summary
Homer is the name given to the poet — or tradition of poets — responsible for the *Iliad* and the *Odyssey*, the two foundational epics of Western literature. Composed in ancient Greece around the 8th century BC, these poems are among the oldest and greatest works of art in human civilization, exploring war, homecoming, heroism, fate, the gods, and the human heart with a depth and beauty that has never been surpassed. Every subsequent tradition of Western literature — Roman, Christian, medieval, Renaissance, and modern — stands in Homer's shadow.
:::

